  <section class="sec">
    <p class="sl">Local knowledge</p>
    <h2>Carlton — Victorian Terrace Density, Party-Wall Chimney Stacks, University Quarter, High Chimney Count Per Street</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Carlton is one of Melbourne's most densely built inner suburbs, developed from the 1850s through the Victorian era as a compact residential area of terrace houses serving the University of Melbourne and the broader inner north. The suburb's housing stock is almost entirely Victorian-era terraces — two and three storey terrace rows in the Drummond Street and Rathdowne Street corridors, single-storey workers' cottages in the southern streets near the CBD, and the grand Victorian terrace rows around Lincoln Square and the University precinct. The defining feature of Carlton's chimney landscape is the party-wall stack — terraces in Carlton were almost universally built with shared chimney stacks running up through the party walls, with each fireplace in the terrace served by a separate flue in the common stack. A Carlton terrace with a living room and bedroom fireplace typically shares a two-flue or three-flue stack with the adjoining home. This configuration requires careful cleaning to ensure correct flue separation is maintained. Many Carlton terraces have been renovated in recent decades, and chimneys that were sealed during a previous renovation period are being reopened by new owners who want working fireplaces as part of the restored period character. We service Carlton and the surrounding inner northern suburbs regularly.</p></div>
  </section>

